On the Kenai Peninsula, this species is known only from Mystery Creek Road. This is the farthwest north and farthest west known population of this species. The nearest population is on Cichagof Island \citep{AKEPIC2017}. \itaxon{Psilocarphus!elatior} is considered to be critically imperiled in British Columbia and endangered in Canada, but it is not listed as a species of conservation concern in the U.S.\ \citep{DouglasIllingworth2004}.  It is common in the Willamette Valley, Oregon \citep{Cronquist1950}.|This species inhabits drying, muddy margins of ephemeral pools and depressions, often in disturbed sites \citep{DouglasIllingworth2004}.  Little is known about interaction with other species, but in California another species of \itaxon{Psilocarphus} is eaten by species of \itaxon{Leporidae} \citep{ZedlerBlack1992}.
